## 5. End-to-end data flow (functional test)

This is the real proof — MQ ↔ Kafka in both directions. Adjust the kafka bin path to your environment.

```
# --- SINK path: Kafka -> MQ ---
# Produce a test message to the outbound topic; the sink connector delivers it to the MQ queue.
oc exec -it -n dev-kafka dev-kafka-cluster-kafka-0 -- bash -c \
  "echo 'SOP-TEST-RTGS-SINK' | bin/kafka-console-producer.sh \
   --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 --topic rtgs.outbound.kafka.topic"
# Then verify on the MQ side (RTGSOutBoundQueue) that the message arrived.

oc exec -it -n dev-kafka dev-kafka-cluster-kafka-0 -- bash -c \
  "echo 'SOP-TEST-NEFT-SINK' | bin/kafka-console-producer.sh \
   --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 --topic neft.outbound.kafka.topic"

# --- SOURCE path: MQ -> Kafka ---
# Put a message on the MQ inbound queue (RTGSInboundQueue / NeftInboundQueue) from the MQ side,
# then confirm it lands on the inbound Kafka topic:
oc exec -it -n dev-kafka dev-kafka-cluster-kafka-0 -- bash -c \
  "bin/kafka-console-consumer.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
   --topic rtgs.inbound.kafka.topic --from-beginning --timeout-ms 10000"

oc exec -it -n dev-kafka dev-kafka-cluster-kafka-0 -- bash -c \
  "bin/kafka-console-consumer.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
   --topic neft.inbound.kafka.topic --from-beginning --timeout-ms 10000"
# Expected: messages placed on the MQ inbound queues appear here.
```

## 6. Stability check (no rebalance churn — the issue from earlier)

```
# Count rebalances/joins in the last 30 min; should be low
oc logs dev-kafka-connect-mq-connect-0 -n dev-kafka --since=30m | grep -c "Joined group"
# Expected: low single digit (initial join + maybe 1). High count = churn.

# No coordinator-unreachable / unknown-member churn
oc logs dev-kafka-connect-mq-connect-0 -n dev-kafka --since=30m \
  | grep -iE "coordinator was unreachable|UNKNOWN_MEMBER_ID" | wc -l
# Expected: 0 or very low

# No task failures / MQ errors
oc logs dev-kafka-connect-mq-connect-0 -n dev-kafka --since=30m \
  | grep -iE "ERROR|MQRC|unrecoverable" | tail -20
# Expected: no MQRC_* errors, no "Task is being killed"
```

A few SOP notes worth recording alongside the commands:

The `2538 / MQRC_HOST_NOT_AVAILABLE` error means the pod can't reach the MQ listener — use the section-4 port checks to triage (it's network/firewall from the pod's egress IP, not the connector config).

If a connector shows `NotReady` but the cluster and pods are healthy, the recovery action is `oc annotate kafkaconnector <name> strimzi.io/restart=true -n dev-kafka`.

If pods run `registry.redhat.io/amq-streams/...` instead of the `kafka-connect-mq:v3` image, the `spec.image` didn't apply — check it's under `spec:` not `spec.template.pod`.

Ports for the record: NEFT = `10.176.10.213(2001)` / SBI_NEFT, RTGS = `10.176.10.213(2005)` / SBI_RTGS, channel `SBIEPAY2.SVRCONN`.

